The paper also involves the analysis of the number of states required for different types of automata, which falls under the scope of computational complexity theory. Hence, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is another likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of subfunctions and witness functions, which are concepts related to discrete mathematics and graph theory. Therefore, cs.DS (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves the use of probabilistic models, which is a topic in information theory. Hence, cs.IT (Information Theory) is another possible sub-category.
